pr_body:
This pull request considers the first milestone for my Google Summer of Code Project. 
The working fork for the project can be found [here](https://github.com/papachristoumarios/volume_approximation). 

The PR contains the following components

* ODE Solvers (located under `include/ode_solvers`).
    * Include file at `ode_solvers.h`.
    * Euler solver at `euler.h`.
    * Runge-Kutta Methods `rk.h` (generic, given by Butcher Tableau).
    * Richardson's (Bulirsch-Stoer) Extrapolation at `bulirsch_stoer.h`.
    * Leapfrog Method  at `leapfrog.h`.
    * Collocation Method (tested with polynomials for the time being). 
    * All solvers admit Neumann conditions (boundary reflections) truncated in a domain of the form `K_1 x K_2 ... K_n` where `K_i` are convex polytopes. 
    * Tests located at `tests/ode_solvers_test.cpp`.  

* Boundary (non-linear) Oracles (located under `include/nlp_oracles`)
    * Intersection of polytope with general curve of the form `sum_i a_i phi_i(t)` using interior point methods and the COIN-OR IPOPT library using the Eigen-wrapper ifopt. Can be used to find the maximum positive intersection point (in H-polytope and V-polytope) in an interval or the minimum positive intersection point (H-polytope / with higher complexity).  
    * Intersection of polytope with general curve of the form `sum_i a_i phi_i(t)` using Newton-Raphson method. 
    * Intersection of polytope with polynomial curve (or using Chebysev basis)  of the form sum_i a_i phi_i(t) using the MPSolve multi-precision polynomial solver. Can also be used with the secular basis `phi_i(t) = a_i / (t - b_i)`.  
    * Functionality is wrapped to existing functionality in `convex_bodies/{hpolytope.h, vpolytope.h}`.
    * Tests included in `tests/boundary_oracles_test.h`. 

By merging this PR 
 * functionality for implementing samplers (Hamiltonian Monte-Carlo, Langevin) is included to volesti
 * an independent ODE solver library can be used for other problems. 

Some functionality may need to be re-reviewed.

Thanks in advance,
Marios

#### Resources 

 1. Lee, Yin Tat, Ruoqi Shen, and Kevin Tian. "Logsmooth Gradient Concentration and Tighter Runtimes for Metropolized Hamiltonian Monte Carlo." arXiv preprint arXiv:2002.04121 (2020).
 2. Chevallier, Augustin, Sylvain Pion, and Frédéric Cazals. "Hamiltonian Monte Carlo with boundary reflections, and application to polytope volume calculations." (2018).
3. [MPSolve](https://github.com/robol/MPSolve)
4. [COIN-OR IPOPT](https://github.com/coin-or/Ipopt)
5. [ifopt](https://github.com/ethz-adrl/ifopt)
6. Afshar, Hadi Mohasel, and Justin Domke. "Reflection, refraction, and Hamiltonian Monte Carlo." Advances in neural information processing systems. 2015.
